&quot;a lot of people have 4G&quot;
Welcome to the real world.
What do they mean by a lot?

If you know you are only storing two languages, they can go directly on the parent table, named english_text and spanish_text. If you are talking about the easyness of storing a hashmap in NoSQL, ie:
    {
    english :&#x27;text&#x27;,
    spanish : &#x27;text&#x27;,
    french: &#x27;text&#x27;
}<p>You can achieve this in the same table with the JSON storage type:<p><a href="http://www.postgresql.org/docs/devel/static/datatype-json.html" rel="nofollow">http://www.postgresql.org/docs/devel/static/datatype-json.ht...</a><p>Really though, a decent ORM will take care of all the foreign key implementation, and a hashmap is well served by a 2nd table called &#x27;texts&#x27; with 3 columns. I can see why you would be opposed to this, because of the extra join but given the right indexes it won&#x27;t be slow at all.
